content: Trying the python 3 course, not very impressed with the app. On the second module text is cut off when trying to review the learning material as well as on the clean sheet. Also when you click the learn button it just opens a random topic. As far as i can see there's no tracking system for which modules you've done. Unless i missed it somehow. The content of the courses seems good as a beginner.
This is a fantastic way to learn small, digestible chunks of python.
codecadamy has great python courses

Really good, would give 5 stars if python 3 course was free, but I understand that the company has to make money someway.

I am currently learning python. The code academy app has convenient 5 minute 'review' and 'practice' activities you can perform daily which really helps sink in previous lessons. Great for days where I am unable to login into code academy for full lessons.
very educative and helps with my python practice

Very good for when you have some understanding of programming. I learnt some python in school (GCSE and currently doing AS) and am learning C# because I want to make some things in Unity, and this app has been a great help so far!

I signed up for the pro version on the black friday deal. I use this app and the desktop website version. I really struggled to apply python while using online courses but Codecademy has helped me understand it way better then i did before. The projects really help you set in the concepts and allows you to practice it which looking at my results shows how important that is for application. It's been a great investment for me so far.
I don't have words to describe.. I loved it. ... From last month I need a application that help me out the exercise problem in python and HTML so when I found out this I really enjoyed it..

Doesn't let you do any of the courses you have signed up for on the web platform. You're restricted to only these options: HTML/CSS, python, javascript, web development, computer science; data science. While this is great, these are not the same courses as the web development. It's more of a "hot topics" highly restricted feed.
